T1  - Open access renewable resources: Trade and trade policy in a two-country model
AU  - Brander, James A
AU  - Scott Taylor, M
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
SP  - 181
EP  - 209
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(97)00029-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199697000299
KW  - International trade policy
KW  - Renewable resources
AB  - This paper develops a two-good, two-country model with national open access renewable resources. We derive an appropriate analog of “factor proportions” for the renewable resource case and link it to trade patterns and to the likelihood of diversified production. The resource importer gains from trade. However, a diversified resource exporting country necessarily suffers a decline in steady state utility resulting from trade, and may lose along the entire transition path. Thus the basic “gains from trade” presumption is substantially undermined by open access resources. Tariffs imposed by the resource importing country always benefit the resource exporter, and may be pareto-improving.
